Hill makes a distinction between <g.y> and <gy> since there is a minimal pair of ''g.yaṅ'' 'sheep' and ''gyaṅ'' 'also, and'. He argues for a distinction between <g.y> /gj/ and <gy> /gʲ/.{{sfn|Hill|2012b}}

==Case system==
[[grammatical case|Case]] morphology is affixed to entire noun phrases, not to individual words (i.e. ''Gruppenflexion''). Old Tibetan distinguishes the same ten cases as [[Classical Tibetan]]:{{sfn|Hill|2012a}}

* [[absolutive case|absolutive]] (morphologically unmarked)
* [[genitive case|genitive]] (གི་ -''gi'',  གྱི་ -''kyi'', ཀྱི་ -''gyi'', འི་ ''-'i'', ཡི་ -''yi'')
* [[agentive case|agentive]] (གིས་ -''gis'', གྱིས་ -''kyis'', ཀྱིས་ -''gyis'', ས་ -''sa'', ཡིས་ -''yis'')
* [[locative case|locative]] (ན་ -''na'')
* [[allative case|allative]] (ལ་ -''la'')
* [[terminative case|terminative]] (རུ་ -''ru'', སུ་ -''su'', ཏུ་ -''tu'', དུ་ -''du'', ར་ -''ra'')
* [[comitative case|comitative]] (དང་ -''dang'')
* [[ablative case|ablative]] (ནས་ -''nas'')
* [[elative case|elative]] (ལས་ -''las'')
* [[comparative case|comparative]] (བས་ -''bas'')

However, whereas the locative, allative, and terminative gradually fell together in Classical Tibetan (and are referred to the indigenous grammatical tradition as the ''la don bdun''), in Old Tibetan these three cases are clearly distinguished.{{sfn|Hill|2011}}

Traditional Tibetan grammarians do not distinguish case markers in this manner, but rather distribute these case morphemes (excluding ''-dang'' and ''-bas'') into the eight cases of [[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]].

==Personal pronouns==
Old Tibetan has three first person singular pronouns ང་ ''nga'', བདག་ ''bdag'', and ཁོ་བོ་ ''kho-bo'', and three first person plural pronouns ངེད་ ''nged'', བདག་ཅག་ ''bdag-cag'', and འོ་སྐོལ་ '' 'o-skol''. The second person pronouns include two singulars ཁྱོད་ ''khyod'' and ཁྱོ(ན)་འདའ་  ''khyo(n)-'da''' and a plural ཁྱེད་ ''khyed''.{{sfn|Hill|2010b}}

